llable minority and a triumphant majority. Focusing on courtroom procedures, police archives, legal activism, and mainstream media coverage, Chatterjee theorizes violence as a form of governance that creates minority populations. By tracing the composition of anti-Muslim violence and the legal structures that transform that violence into the making of minorities and majorities, Chatterjee demonstrates that violence is intrinsic to liberal democracy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aEthnic conflictzIndia2DLC. 0aEthnic conflictzIndia. 0aMinoritiesxViolence againstzIndia2DLC. 0aMinoritiesxViolence againstzIndia. 0aMuslimsxViolence againstzIndia2DLC. 0aMuslimsxViolence againstzIndia. 0aPolitical violencezIndiaxReligious aspects2DLC. 0aPolitical violencezIndiaxReligious aspects. 0aReligion and politicszIndia2DLC. 0aReligion and politicszIndia. 0aSocial conflictzIndia2DLC. 0aSocial conflictzIndia. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311099775040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478024293?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478024293423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478024293/original  a978-3-11-099775-0  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles